---

There was a time when writing code was the bottleneck.

You had an idea, and the limiting factor was your ability to translate that idea into working software. Syntax, APIs, and edge cases slowed you down just enough to force you to think.

That constraint is mostly gone.

Tools like Claude Code, Cursor, Codex, and newer agentic IDEs have flipped the dynamic. You can generate entire features in minutes—and sometimes whole systems—through iterative loops of prompting, execution, and refinement.

But the result of AI-assisted code (and the velocity that comes with it) hasn’t eliminated technical debt. It’s just changed its shape.


## Technical Debt Under a New Guise

Modern coding agents will usually give you syntactically correct code that builds on the first try. In many cases, it’s better than what an average developer could produce under the same time pressure.

That used to be the hard part.

Now the problem is different: local correctness doesn’t guarantee system-level coherence.

What emerges is still technical debt—just in new forms.


### Comprehension Debt

You didn’t hand-write this code. You prompted an agent, reviewed the output, maybe tweaked a few lines, and moved on.

Your understanding is shallower as a result.

There’s a growing gap between what the system does and what you can confidently explain. That gap is what I’d call *comprehension debt*.

It doesn’t show up during development. It shows up later—when something breaks and you’re tracing through code that technically makes sense, but feels unfamiliar.

I’ve hit this recently: debugging an issue where everything “looked right,” tests passed, but I still couldn’t explain why a certain abstraction existed. That’s the moment you realize you’re dealing with a system you don’t fully own.

The problem isn’t that the code is bad. It’s that the context was never really yours.


### Consistency Debt

AI is very good at solving the problem directly in front of it.

It’s much less reliable at maintaining a consistent philosophy across a codebase.

You start to see:
- Multiple patterns for the same concern
- Slightly different abstractions solving identical problems
- Naming and structure that drift over time

Individually, everything is reasonable. Collectively, the system loses its shape.

Consistency used to be enforced by friction. Now it has to be enforced deliberately.


### Over-Engineering

AI has seen every design pattern ever written.

And it tends to reach for them.

You ask for a simple feature and get:
- An interface
- A factory
- A strategy pattern
- A layer of indirection no one explicitly asked for

None of it is wrong. It’s just unnecessary.

Over-engineering used to be something you’d occasionally introduce by accident. Now it’s often the default output unless you push back.


### Hidden Dependency Debt

AI will happily introduce libraries to solve narrow problems—parsing, validation, formatting.

Each choice is reasonable in isolation.

Over time though:
- Build complexity creeps up
- Upgrade paths get fragile
- The system becomes harder to reason about

The coupling is subtle at first. Then one day a version bump breaks three unrelated things and you realize how tangled it’s become.


## “Vibe Coding” and the Illusion of Progress

There’s a new development loop that feels incredibly efficient:

You describe what you want.  
The system generates it.  
You refine it.  
It works.  

Repeat.

It feels like flow. It feels like momentum.

But it’s easy to confuse *output* with *understanding*.

When the loop is that fast, you stop interrogating decisions. You stop asking whether the approach is actually the right one, because it already produces results.

Add in how confidently LLMs explain their solutions, and it’s easy to end up with a system that works—but is quietly bloated or misaligned.

Speed doesn’t just accelerate development. It compresses doubt.

And some amount of doubt is where good engineering decisions usually come from.


## Agentic IDEs Don’t Remove Debt — They Shift It

Agentic IDEs push this even further.

They can:
- Scan and “understand” your codebase (`/init`)
- Generate tests automatically
- Execute code and observe outputs
- Iterate in closed loops until things pass

At first glance, this looks like a solution.

Consistency improves. Tests exist. Feedback loops are tighter.

And to be fair, these tools *do* raise the baseline quality of what gets produced.

But they also introduce a different dynamic.

You can now end up with a system that is:
- internally consistent
- well-tested
- continuously self-correcting

…without actually understanding it.

The debt hasn’t disappeared. It’s been pushed somewhere else.

> AI can maintain systems you don’t understand—and that’s a different kind of risk.

Agentic loops are good at optimizing within a system.

They’re not good at questioning whether the system itself is well-designed.

They won’t decide:
- whether a dependency should exist
- whether an abstraction is justified
- whether the architecture makes sense long-term

They operate within whatever frame you give them.

If that frame is off, they’ll reinforce it—quickly.


## The Compression of Design Time

Friction used to act as a forcing function.

If something was painful to implement, you naturally spent more time deciding whether it was worth doing that way.

AI removes that friction.

Now you can generate a complex abstraction just as easily as a simple one.

So you do.

The result is a system that accumulates complexity faster than it accumulates understanding.

Design used to be constrained by effort.

Now it’s constrained by discipline.


## The Ownership Gap

There’s a shift happening in how developers relate to their systems.

We’re moving from builders to curators.

Instead of constructing systems piece by piece, we assemble them from generated outputs. We review, edit, accept.

But ownership doesn’t really come from approval. It comes from construction.

When you’ve wrestled with a problem, you understand its edges. You remember the tradeoffs. You know where it might break.

When you haven’t, the system feels slightly external—even if you wrote the prompt.

That gap matters.

Because when things go wrong, responsibility doesn’t disappear. It just becomes harder to act on.


## Redefining Senior Engineering

AI has raised the floor.

A junior engineer with the right prompts can produce output that looks like senior-level code.

But the ceiling hasn’t moved. If anything, it matters more now.

The value of a senior engineer isn’t just writing better code.

It’s deciding what should exist at all.

That means:
- Defining system boundaries
- Enforcing architectural consistency
- Setting constraints that guide implementation
- Evaluating tradeoffs before they get encoded into the system

The skill is shifting from *how to code* to *what to build*.

And that’s a harder problem.


## Managing AI-Driven Technical Debt

You don’t solve this by avoiding AI.

You solve it by being more deliberate in how you use it.


### Enforce Architectural Constraints

If you don’t define structure, the system will drift.

Be explicit about:
- Patterns
- Layer boundaries
- Naming conventions

In practice, this often means encoding constraints directly into how you use your tools—prompt templates, reusable “skills”, system-level guidelines.

AI follows constraints well.

It just won’t invent them for you.


### Require Explanation, Not Just Output

Don’t just accept code. Ask for reasoning.

- Why this approach?
- What tradeoffs were considered?
- What assumptions are being made?

If the explanation feels shallow, the implementation probably is too.


### Run Coherence Audits

Step back occasionally and look at the system as a whole.

Not file-by-file—system-wide.

Ask:
- Does this feel like one cohesive system?
- Are similar problems solved in similar ways?
- Is there a clear architectural story?

If not, you’re accumulating debt—even if everything technically works.


### Be Intentional About Slowing Down

Not everything should be fast.

Some decisions deserve friction.

If something introduces:
- A new abstraction
- A new dependency
- A new pattern

That’s usually a signal to pause.

Speed is a tool. It doesn’t have to be the default.


## Closing Thoughts

AI has made code cheap.

It hasn’t made good systems cheap.

If anything, they’re more expensive now—because the limiting factor isn’t effort anymore, it’s judgment.

The risk isn’t just generating bad code.

It’s generating systems that are internally consistent, well-tested, and still fundamentally misaligned.

Technical debt used to be visible.

Now it can be maintained, reinforced, and hidden—all at the same time.

And that’s a much harder thing to untangle later.
